desc: How Iâ€™ve traveled for 13 years ğŸ‘‡ (Save & share with someone who can relate!) Firstly, & honesty though I am very happy being single, especially after a painful breakup. I think itâ€™s important to give yourself time to heal & work on fixing your own energy before taking on other peoples ğŸ«¶ Secondly, hereâ€™s HOW Iâ€™ve traveled so much: At 18 I went to Australia solo on a working holiday visa & worked for pretty much the whole time! Then visited some of Asia ğŸ‰  During my university summers I went interrailling (thanks student overdraft) & worked a summer season in Greece as a waitress.  Post uni I worked 2 full time hour jobs (9-5 office & bar work evenings/ weekend), saved Â£3,500 & went away for 2.5 years.  I did this through budget backpacking, a working holiday visa in New Zealand for 2 years & volunteering for accom in Tonga & Hawaii.  Then I worked as a European Trip Leader for 2 years(thanks Covid)! I lead trips through a mix of 25 countries! Iâ€™d save during my trip leading seasons & use this money for personal travel in my months off between winter & summer. I also god discounts on Egypt & a trip around 6 African countries as I worked for a tour company! May 2021 I left the UK, started teaching English online, got a fully remote job & now I am a content creator, travel coach & social media strategist for brands. desc: Europe's passport-free travel zone will be welcoming Croatia.  EU countries today voted on whether or not to admit the three nations into the so-called Schengen zone - a pact between countries to abolish border checks for those travelling between their territories. Croatia received unanimous support from the 26 Schengen member states. If you were using Croatia as a base to reset your Schengen day count you might have to find a different base.  And on the other hand it means more borderless travel for those that have secured a residency or citizenship in Schengen zone.  The world is becoming a smaller place.  #freedomofmovement #borderless #moveabroad #sovereignindividual #sovereigncitizen #croatia #schengencountries #schengenvisa #digitalnomad #nomadlife

desc: Working as a digital nomad in Antigua and Barbuda has the following benefits: â€¢Easy internet access. With an internet speed fixed 20.95 Mbps and mobile 33.80 Mbps, you can work in any part of the world from Antigua & Barbuda, feeling at home or office. â€¢Smooth visa application process. Applying for the Antigua & Barbuda digital nomad visa is fairly easy, and everything is done online. Moreover, you will have to wait only 14 days for an answer. â€¢Tax exemption. As a digital nomad, you are exempt from ping income taxes in Antigua and Barbuda. â€¢Warm climate. With a tropical savannah climate, Antigua & Barbuda has pleasing year-round weather. The best time to visit Antigua & Barbuda is November to April, when it is least rainy and hot. â€¢Delicious cuisine. Antigua & Barbuda has become a food destination because of its fresh seafood, flavored dishes, and top-notch rum. This place is a haven for rum distilleries and sugar plantations. â€¢Leisure activities. In Antigua & Barbuda, you can enjoy a variety of activities. Among the activities you can enjoy are exploring rainforests, swimming with stingrays, biking, kayaking, diving, snorkeling, sailing, and fishing. Michael and Acacia are professional videographers and photographers and find that their nomadic lifestyle has allowed their business to expand.  This video was brought to you by Orion by Up-Switch. desc: This might sound silly, but..  I was feeling restless and unproductive during my stay in General Luna in the south of Siargao. I sensed the need for a getaway, a place remote and serene, away from the hustle and bustle of the busy hub and social life. âœ¨ So, on a whim, I packed a small bag, strapped my surfboard onto my scooter, and headed north, all the way to the most northern point of Siargao Island. The 1.5-hour drive was filled with breathtaking scenery that only grew more beautiful as I ventured further. Along the way, I would pause, absorbing the incredible beauty that surrounded me, realizing that I was healing from something, anything. ğŸ¤ When I arrived at my hotel, just a short walk from one of the most stunning, uncrowded beaches with crystal-clear waters, adorned by fishing boats and encircled by countless palm trees, I knew I had found my sanctuary. My days were spent either surfing alone, catching those perfect waves, or sharing the waves with just one other person. It was an incredible experience, feeling the power of the ocean and the freedom it brings. I dedicated time to building my website for @aryclub.official, finally ticking off substantial tasks while immersing myself in the beauty and tranquility of the surroundings. It goes without saying that I fell head over heels for the north of Siargao; thereâ€™s an undeniable magic in this area. The experience was a powerful reminder that sometimes, all it takes is a spontaneous journey to reconnect with ourselves and find solace in the beauty of nature. I feel a renewed sense of purpose and energy, ready to take on new challenges and continue the journey of reinventing myself. ğŸ«¶  If youâ€™re ever in Siargao; you now know where to go ğŸ¦‹ #SiargaoDiaries #surfergirl #digitalnomadlife  #surfinglife #reels #tropicalvibes #motivationalreel #inspirationalreel #healthandwellness #thatgirl #dailyhabit #Siargaoisland #siargao #Philippinesparadise #gophilippines #IslandLife #travelinspiration

stickersText:

', 'Thenâ€¦ there were 3 major tragedies at home ğŸ’” I moved back to the US without a plan.  I tried to fit in, but living abroad had changed me.

desc: when i shared the places i lived in my 20â€™s in a post last week, I had a lot of qâ€™s asking howâ€¦ and more importantly I noticed that there was perhaps a misconception that you need a lot of money to be able to do it, which (whilst helpful of course) definitely isnâ€™t a must! Straight after university I left the UK for New York, with only small amount in the bank but a biggg desire to experience living everywhere iâ€™d ever dreamed of before iâ€™d have to â€˜settle downâ€™ in one stable job. and by either making money while abroad or finding ways to live there while spending almost nothing, i managed to moved to six countries throughout my entire 20â€™s. for the most part, it did mean living pretty minimally, but the experiences were anything but âœ¨ğŸ«¶ğŸ½ i would also like to add one thing though - if i was 20 again in this era right now, i would go straight to finding ways i can become a digital nomad to be able to travel freely long term whilst earning money online (which is what i do now too). desc: â€œwould you be able to share what living in so many different places in your 20â€™s taught you?â€  a question that came in my comments a couple of weeks ago as i was turning 33 and one that i wanted to answer in full...  my 20â€™s were adventurous, unforgettable and my greatest teacher. i learned that possibilities and opportunities depend more on your mindset and how you view them rather than logistics or â€˜limitations.â€™ if you believe anything is possible, it will be...  i learned that you need not worry about losing closeness with your friends and family .. when you already have strong foundations, they will not only stay no matter how far or for how long you travel, but support, accept and love that part of you too. i learned that everyone has a story, to not be judgemental, to remain open, to embrace opportunities that may spontaneously arrive and let go of plans that may instead fall through ..  i learned that when you expand, your own world and your views, you can no longer fit into conventional societal expectations, even if you try. freedom becomes part of your dna and anything less is hard to settle for.  as a result of that i learned thatâ€™s worth trying everything to create or keep a life you absolutely love, rather than staying on a path where you know you wonâ€™t be happy. and that you can change course and start over as many times as you want.  and most importantly i learned that following my heart is the only way to feel peace. above security, material things and what society deems as success, true wealth is determined by how much time you spend doing the things you love.  the list could go on. my 20â€™s taught me a lot and itâ€™s laid the foundation of life in my 30â€™s knowing more than ever who i am, what i like and dislike, what my values are, whatâ€™s important to me and how i want to live.  but the most important teaching of all, is that the lessons and learning never endâ€¦ and for that, Iâ€™m grateful. âœ¨  . . . . . desc: in my early 20â€™s i always had the belief that one day i would need to settle down, get a â€˜real jobâ€™ and work my way up the corporate ladder as so many of us do. and this is the reason that whilst travelling, i always made sure that i did â€˜something for my cvâ€™ whether it be working at different companies, taking a language course in the country i was in, volunteering or doing extra studies along the way.  at 25 i entered my new office, to work in PR for an international agency in Berlin. and to be brief, it was three years and three promotions later, nearing burnout and feeling my soul slip away, that i got the message. â€œthis life is not meant for you.â€  and i knew it to be true. so at 28, with no financial reserve but a lot of drive to change direction, i quit my job and founded my own business (@homemade_studio ğŸ˜˜), then one more during lockdown (@nawaste.co) whilst also freelancing on the side.  it took a fair few years of hard work and fair few more sacrifices, but i made it back to having the freedom to experience living/working from different places around the world â€¦ and this time, purely on my terms and without an expiry date. ğŸ¦‹ people ask if the decision to was scary. and i can honestly say that it wasnâ€™t â€¦ it was the thought of staying where I was and where that path was heading that terrified me much much more âœ¨ i share this because your soul knows. if you feel called to have a lifestyle like this, not rooted in the traditional 9-5 path, itâ€™s because youâ€™re meant to. and you can ğŸ¤ . . . . . #cre#createyourdreamlifeo#slowtravellerd#madetottravele#freedomlifestylee#freedomlifef#lifejourneyt#authenticexperiencec#localfindsd#hiddengemsc#secretspotso#slowtravelu#founderstoryg#digitalnomadlifestyleg#digitalnomadlifere#freespiritl#fulltimetravellerm#womentravelsolol#solofemaletravelad#madeformorei#spiritualgrowthjourneyl#selftrustrsonalgrowthjourney

sama2 bekerja secara online.', 'Bedanya remote work nggak terikat peraturan atau punya peraturan perusahaan yg bebas terkait tempat & waktu bekerja. Mau kerja di pantai, gunung, negara/kota lain, beach club, cafe, timezone yg beda juga aman.. asal ada internet.', 'Sementara, walau sama2 online, WFH somehow tetap tunduk dg peraturan2 tertentu terkait waktu & tempatnya and biasanya di set untuk kasih suasana baru ke pekerjanya. Cuma, kasarannya tidak sebebas remote working.', 'Dan dengan kebebasan yg dimiliki sama orang2 yg kerja remote work muncul juga life style digital nomad. Lifestyle dimana orang traveling atau hidup berpindah2 di banyak kota/negara yg berbeda sambil kerja secara online.

desc: Replying to @generic_user_name_  Finding a remote job that allows you to travel both nationally internationally can be a really tough time especially if you're trying to live the digital nomad or full time traveler lifestyle like I am. There are career search tools online that I was able to find such as trulyremote.co and there are companies that do seemingly hire international remote workers such as Spotify, Zapier and Atlassian.  The other best option is  To choose a career that allows you to travel remote regardless or makes it more likely such as copywriting, freelance work, e-commerce, software development,  Is teaching English online, etc.  My last piece of advice would be to travel to a place and work there like with a Woking Holiday Vusa or to work a contract job in the United States to save up enough money to travel internationally.  Let me know if you have any more questions on working remotely internationally and I hope this helps! #digitalnomad #digitalnomadlifestyle #fulltimetravel #fulltimetraveler #fulltimetravelers #remotejobs #digitalnomadlife #digitalnomadjobs #remotejobsearch

desc: People always tell me how they want to travel like me or have my life, and I have two things to say to that: 1. My life isn't all that you see on social media. There's a lot (both good and bad) that I don't post here. I have my issues, just like anyone else. But perhaps most importantly, I don't travel as much as it looks like on social media. Don't get me wrong, I travel a lot, but as an aspiring content creator I have to post travel content on a daily basis, several times a day, across multiple platforms. I can assure you I don't travel every day, or every week or every month. 2. Everyone comes from a different background and I've been very lucky when it comes to travel. I'm not going to sit here and deny my priviledge.  That said, no one handed this life to me. The content creation, solo travel and potentially being a full-time traveler, that was all me. It all started with a decision to change the way I lived and take risks in order to pursue what I wanted. And more importantly, action followed that decision. That is the most important thing. #travellife #travellifestyle #travellifeâœˆï¸ #digitalnomad #digitalnomadlife #digitalnomadlifestyle #digitalnomadtravel

desc: The digital nomad Visa is the perfect  Way to see and live in another country if you have a job that is remote or if you work for yourself. These countries will let you live there as long as you can prove that you make a certain income which most of the time is their minimum wage. Here are all the countries that I mentioned,  Norway Bahamas Portugal Germany  Barbados Greece Iceland Romania  Indonesia Italy Spain Taiwan and Mexico.  I also mentioned Australia New Zealand Ireland South Korea and Singapore do not have this program but will let you stay there for a year with a  working holiday Visa which I can talk about in another video.  As a full time traveler and digital nomad and backpacker these are some of the best tools to use to see the world for cheap, it is also a great alternative to the gap year. desc: Replying to @lisaserota  Here are all my budget travel tips and travel recommendations for someone going to visit Tokyo, Japan.  1st I would recommend  Going to all the different cities within Tokyo, Japan such as shinjuku shibuya asakusa rapungi and so on.  Then I would also recommend going to Tokyo Disneyland and sea, the studio ghibli museum, the Ramen museum, TeamLABS Tokyo and some of the more popular places like Sensoji temple, Tokyo sky tree, Tsukiji fish market, and the Imperial palace.  As for food I would recommend trying yakaniku and ramen as well as my favorite Japanese chicken Katsu curry, CoCo Ichibanya is great quick and easy for katsu curry but I may also recommend somewhere that isn't a chain that specializes in katsu curry. Additionally, I would also recommend going outside of the city to Fuji, Kyoto, Osaka and Himeji with the JR Rail pass. #tokyotravel #visittokyo #budgettraveller #budgettraveltips #fulltimetravel #fulltimetraveller #digitalnomads #japantraveltips #visitjapan #digitalnomadlifestyle

desc: I swam aboard a sexy manâ€™s boat this day, for real ğŸ‘€ğŸ‘‡ (Save & share with someone whoâ€™d do this) What really happened in this video: a group of friends and I went out on a boat in Ibiza where we drank rose, danced, swam & lived our best lives. But carried on anywayâ€¦ I also love my friends in the background joining in the groove ğŸ¤£ On this day I also hijacked a neighbouring boat ğŸ˜‚. I saw a sailing boat close to ours with some beautiful men on board & it looked like they lived in it so I wanted to know their storyâ€¦ I jumped into the water with my bucket hat on, swam over and started chatting to them. They gave me a beer and let me have a look on the boat (it was close to our boat though & i made sure I was in sight of my friends at all times as safety first). I then jumped off the bow & swam back to my friendsâ€¦ it felt like a true mamma mia moment ğŸ˜† Turns out the owner is an Italian guy who lets people live on his boat all summer to help him out sailing around the Med. desc: re-meeting Paris as different versions of myself ğŸ¥°ğŸ¤ the importance of the notion â€˜enjoy the nowâ€™ that we hear so often took on a whole deeper meaning for me during my time in Paris.  walking the streets and remembering my â€˜9 years agoâ€™ version of me who had done the same. finding myself sat here in the very spot that was once an abandoned hospital and my secret place to enter at night with the notre dame in full view, a friend and a bottle of wine in hand. i mean, i remember clearly feeling that it was a special experience then â€¦ but i hadnâ€™t considered how much and how those moments would never be replicated.  because at some point over the last 9 years, the hospital reopened and itâ€™s no longer the place with deserted hallways i once knew. now itâ€™s only accessible if you are a visiting a patient â€¦ or you manage to charm the security guard with nostalgic stories until they surprisingly reach under the desk for a visitors pass, hand it to you with a secret smile and nod and permit you entry ğŸ˜….  so on this day, by chance and with luck, i sat in this same spot for perhaps the last time in my life ğŸ¥¹. taking it all in.  and i thought about how moments become memories so quickly and how often, we may not fully appreciate and see them as the unique moment in time that they are.   and this is the re-reminder i was given. to fully enjoy, be present and conscious on every single trip taken and every single experience ... because yes, you may have the chance to be in the same places again, physically â€¦ but the experience of you, in this moment, at this age, as the you that you are right now â€¦ that will only ever happen once. . . . . . #madetot#madetotravely#createyourdreamlifei#intuitivelivinga#slowtravellerm#freedomlifestylem#freedomlifeu#lifejourneya#slowtravela#slowtravellerl#digitalnomadlifestylei#freespiritr#womentravelsolom#solofemaletravelp#rooftopview##parisa#notredames#travelstoriesi#expatlifeifestyle

desc: Todayâ€™s #travelvlog was an interesting one! Our bike route was a bit more difficult with the unfinished road, which was muddy and filled with water from the storm. We were prepared to have our feet soaked in mud, but thankfully there were enough rocks for us to stand on to push our bikes through!  The mud dried on our bike supee fast though, making it difficult to clip in. We stopped at a little store to have ice cream and some food, and to use the rest of our euros! Then we crossed the border into Serbia!  Another wild storm tonight, and this time the wifi went out as did the water. We still had cell service, so we continued to work with data. Seeing the aftermath of the storm was shocking, especially seeing the lamposts that were snapped in half! Super grateful that we were inside the whole time!  #digitalnomad #digitalnomadlifestyle #biketouring #biketour #serbia #storm

desc: slow travel isn't always necessarily to do with time. it's true that we don't always have the opportunity to spend a few weeks or months in one place, but even still, we can slow down our pace.  avoid trying to squeeze everywhere and everything in, making a checklist of must do's and a plan to see them back to back, let go of spending time in the popular places that actually don't make your soul light up and release any feelings of guilt that may come with believing that you're seeing less. by doing this, you'll come away with actually experiencing more. go on long walks without a set direction, stopping at whichever place, restaurant or cafe that 'just feels good,' to you, be open to long conversations with strangers, and spend some leisurely time watching the world go by and soaking it all in. by all means, have a little pre-list of highlights you'd love to see, but stay open to the flow and the beauty that comes with going slow. ğŸ“aix en provence . . . . . #madeformore #createyourdreamlife #madetottravel #freedomlifestyle #freedomlife #digitalnomadlifestyle #slowtravel #slowtraveller #slowtravelling #lifejourney #authenticexperience #localfinds #localtips #freespirit #fulltimetraveller #womentravelsolo #solofemaletravel #solofemaletraveler #solofemaletraveller #provence #provencelife #aixenprovence

stickersText:
['How I traveled the ğŸŒ as Digital Nomad PART 2', 'I got my first remote job offer while I was on a 2-week trip to Costa Rica.

 I was sitting by the pool on the phone with my new boss and he said, â€œas long as you have good wifi and are online when you need to be online, I donâ€™t care where you are.â€ ', 'I called Spirit Airline to see if I could change my flight to a later date & MIRACULOUSLY I got a full refund! Suddenly I was in Central America with a full-time remote job, no return flightâ€¦ & a party I wanted to attend in Nicaragua!', 'The party was AMAZING. I couldnâ€™t believe I didnâ€™t have to go home after it!

I promised myself there was no way Iâ€™d F* this up & Iâ€™d do anything to be the MOST RELIABLE employee ever. After a month of traveling, my boss was happy & started giving me better projects.', 'I moved on from Nica to Colombia. Then to Ecuador, Brazilâ€¦ at first I was only SOLO TRAVELING but eventually I started  meeting other people who called themselves â€œDigital Nomads,â€ (I never heard the term before!)', 'The more nomad friends I made, the more I felt like my travel lifestyle was sustainableâ€¦ & it WAS.

I ended up living out of my suitcase for 5 years straight! I traveled to 60 countries while making good money & so many amazing friends.', 'After years at my job I quit in the middle of the pandemic to help people become digital nomads too. Now Iâ€™m a coach!

I use my intuitive gifts to determine which remote business they should create & then guide them through creating their biz and setting up their own traveling lifestyle.']

Bismillah pasti ada jalan, karena setiap hari selalu ada kerjaannya. Dari dalam dan luar negeri semua ada. desc: Email I send after an interview when I donâ€™t get the job. Itâ€™s easy to take rejection personally But there are many reasons why you donâ€™t get a job 1. desc: I started my Etsy shop in March/April 2022. I was due with my second baby, coming in early May, and my goal was to have my Etsy shop up before I gave birth.  I figured to get sales; I would have to promote my shop on social media. So I set it up, planning to return to it a few months post-baby.  May baby was born. I got zero sales.  June, I wasnâ€™t paying attention, but I got a few organic sales.  July, I realized I was getting a few sales here and there. I think I made $158 that month.  August, I dove back into it, hoping to make an extra $500 a month passively from my shop. I tweaked my product, bringing me to my first $1k. This video explains the strategy that I used: @Des | Selling Digital Products  In the last year, my shop has made over $45k in revenue. desc: [Freelancing Life] Besides doing a 9 to 5 job, I also have some freelance jobs as my additional income. Doing a freelance job while also having a full-time job mengharuskan saya untuk mengorbankan beberapa hal, seperti waktu tidur yang akhirnya lebih sedikit, waktu weekend, dan kesenangan masa muda lainnya. Beberapa minggu ini saya coba mengubah pola kerja saya, dari yang sebelummya kerja sampai larut setelah selesai full-time, menjadi kerja lebih pagi sebelum full-time. I try to sleep as early as possible setelah selesai kerjaan full-time, kemudian bangun lebih pagi untuk ngerjain side project or freelance job. Tantangan untuk terus belajar hal baru seringkali datang dari freelance job and for me this is my chance to sharpen my skills. For me, selagi masih muda, selagi energi nya masih banyak dan otak nya masih kuat untuk belajar hal-hal baru, mengorbankan kesenangan-kesenangan jangka pendek bukanlah hal yang perlu disesali. I love doing my coding job, so it's not a big deal for me. #softwaredeveloper #softwareengineerlife #softwareengineer #coding #codinglife #freelance #flutterdeveloper #remotework #workfromhome #dayinmylife #dayinthelife #workfromanywhere
